The 45-year-old defendant was found guilty of a massacre in an attack on two nightclubs in the popular tourist area of Kuta that killed 202 people, including 88 Australians, and injured dozens more.
He was also found guilty on a number of other terrorism-related charges, including a spate of church bombings across Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
Prosecutors have demanded a life sentence, although they could have insisted that the man, dubbed a &quot;bomber&quot; for his reputation as a master bomb maker, should be sentenced to death.
