Power engineers of Dnepropetrovsk region have launched a unique program to save... stork nests
In the old days, in order to bring storks to the court, the villagers installed a wheel from a cart on a high pole, and the heavy nest held well on it.
Such special supports have not been installed for a long time, so the storks have chosen the poles of power lines - intertwined branches rest on wires, thanks to which the stork house stands securely.
Grandmother Anya, near whose house in the village of Ivanovka, Petrikovsky district, a stork family has been living for twenty years, began to notice how the nest is sinking, despite all the efforts of its inhabitants.
Birds put new branches on top, and the bottom layer has already sunk between the wires, is about to collapse.
Of course, it’s a pity for the family of storks that nested at the farmstead every year, brought out and fed three or four chicks over the summer, but I don’t want to be left without light either.
As soon as the birds flew away to warmer climes, Anya&#39;s grandmother called the Tsarichansky Distribution Zone, which owns the support.
And I did not even expect that they would respond so quickly.
When our specialists arrived in Ivanovka, they were surprised that the nest was still holding on, - said Sergei Berezovsky, technical director of DTEK Dneprooblenergo.
On the wires, which were, in fact, already inside the nest, weighing 150 - 200 kilograms, corrosion began.
At any moment, the birds could die from an electric discharge.
Yes, and local residents risked being left without electricity due to damaged wires.
Therefore, linemen began an operation to save the nest, and not for the first time in our practice.
Ornithologists from the Dnepropetrovsk National University helped, who developed a nest transfer scheme.
They also conducted trainings for employees of regional networks.
The well-known Dnepropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko advised power engineers at all stages of nest reconstruction.
To begin with, it was calculated that more than 50 stork &quot;apartments&quot; are in disrepair in the region.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms resembling a funnel were welded.
The base was braided with willow branches, and then the old nest was moved there.
According to experts, it is enough to lay old branches as a base for the birds to recognize the nest and return to it.
Later, the storks themselves will complete their dwelling.
A month ago, the first nest was reconstructed in the village of Peschanka, Novomoskovsky district.
A new reinforced concrete pole was placed next to the electric pole and a platform with an old, already inhabited nest was placed on it.
The entire operation cost the power engineers nine thousand hryvnias.
And the other day, the same housewarming took place in the village of Ivanovka, Petrikovsky district, in the courtyard of grandmother Anya.
Here the platform was fixed in its original place, only raised above the wires.
Ornithologists are confident that cautious, conservative birds will not even notice in the spring that their &quot;apartment&quot; has undergone a major overhaul.
By the end of the year, the same reconstruction is expected for four more nests in the Pokrovsky and Tsarichansky districts of the Dnepropetrovsk region.
By the way, while some save rare birds, others ruthlessly kill them.
Recently, sad news spread throughout the region - in the village of Ust-Kamenka, Apostolovsky district, on the day of the opening of pheasant hunting, poachers shot a swan family that lived on a local pond for fun.
Noble birds were not at all afraid of people - the locals fed them and did not offend them.
When the villagers, having heard the shots, ran to the pond, four handsome swans were already lying dead on the water.
Now employees of the Apostolovsky regional department of militia find out who shot the birds listed in the Red Book.
American Boeing stuck in Chita preparing for takeoff
An American aircraft that conducted observation flights over Russian territory under the Open Skies Treaty and made an unscheduled landing in Chita on Wednesday, November 1, at 8:30 Moscow time, will leave the air harbor of the city.
The airport management allowed the plane to take off, having received money for fuel.
As reported at the airport, the plane will fly to Ulan-Ude.
According to other sources, he will head to the United States.
As reported, a plane flying to Ulan-Ude landed in the Trans-Baikal Territory due to fog.
Due to unpaid bills, he was not allowed to leave the Chita airport.
There are 30 people on board the plane, including the crew, they spent two nights at the airport, ITAR-TASS reports.
According to the Russian Foreign Ministry, under the terms of the Open Skies Treaty, people on board the aircraft do not have the right to leave the Chita airport, they can pass border control only at two Russian airports - in Kubinka and Ulan-Ude.
The Open Skies Treaty was signed in 1992 and has 34 member states.
Observation flights are carried out over the territories of Russia, the USA, Canada, and European countries.
The main tasks of the Treaty are the development of transparency, assistance in monitoring the implementation of agreements in the field of arms control, expansion of opportunities for preventing crises and resolving crisis situations within the framework of the OSCE and other international organizations.
