Cocaine-addicted lawyer who tipped off gang leader about police investigation jailed
Basharat Ditta, 42, passed information to crime boss Neil Scarborough
The lawyer was afraid that his secret drug addiction would be exposed
He was sentenced to three years in prison by the Liverpool Crown Court.
A prestigious lawyer who told a drug lord about a major police investigation because he feared his secret drug addiction would be exposed was jailed for three years.
Basharat Ditta, 42, supplied crime boss Neil Scarborough with classified information about an investigation into his drug trafficking activities after he came under threat from his cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed Bash and nicknamed by criminals as a &quot;tough lawyer&quot;, was arrested at his home in 2011 after a police operation to spy on Scarborough, whom he had previously represented in a drug-related trial.
Officers spotted Scarborough, 32, leaving three packets of cocaine outside a lawyer&#39;s home in Blackburn, Lancashire while he was at a bar association dinner with colleagues.
The investigation revealed that Ditta &quot;regularly used&quot; a Class A drug after tests showed traces of cocaine in his hair, on his wallet and on credit cards.
For eight months from January to August 2011, he tried to illegally obtain information about the arrests of two people on behalf of Scarborough, as well as one of his accomplices.
All four suspects were at the time under police surveillance as part of a large-scale investigation into the activities of a criminal organization selling heroin and cocaine in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
They and 32 others were later jailed after police seized £1.5m worth of heroin and cocaine and more than £200,000 in cash in a series of raids.
Ditta, 42, leaked information to criminals out of fear that his cocaine addiction would be exposed.
Ditta, who works for Blackburn-based law firm Forbes Solicitors, was shamed at Liverpool Crown Court today after being found guilty of two counts of willful obstruction of justice following a three-week trial at Liverpool Crown Court.
He admitted to possession of cocaine at one of the previous court hearings.
The lawyer&#39;s exposure came after police investigating Scarborough found he had been on the phone with Ditt on a regular basis since February 2011.
Two detectives tracked the suspect and found him walking up to Ditt&#39;s home in Blackburn and placing 60% pure drugs in a black golf glove under the lawyer&#39;s dustbins.
Shortly after the transfer, Scarborough called Ditt repeatedly, who was at a dinner at Blackburn Rovers&#39; Ewood Park football stadium.
The lawyer returned home for drugs; nine conversations took place between them.
The court learned that Ditta was a &quot;regular user&quot; of cocaine after tests found traces of the Class A drug in his hair, wallet and on his credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but denied using cocaine, said he had spoken to the suspected dealer because he was a client, and insisted that their communication was a &quot;lawyer&#39;s secret.&quot;
During his detention, Ditta took his wallet and tried to take out several credit cards, but they were all confiscated, and a hair sample was also taken from him.
When questioned by the police, he said that along with the workplace, he also had a home office, and clients came to his house on legal matters.
However, the court learned that after important arrests, he called the largest participants in drug trafficking, a number of whom he had previously represented in court, to tell what detectives know about them.
In her accusatory speech, Ann White said, &quot;If anyone knows not to break the law, it&#39;s a criminal defense attorney.&quot;
Mr. Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal defense lawyer by getting too intimate with certain clients.
The contact we&#39;re talking about is not just a drug dealer, but a drug dealer supplying drugs to his own lawyer.
Some of his conversations would certainly turn out to be legitimate, since he was their lawyer.
However, this has largely gone beyond the usual lawyer-client relationship.
He obstructed the police investigation as much as possible in order to allow these individuals to continue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta did not honor his profession, but dishonored it.
He got too close to certain clients, Scarborough in particular, and let his lack of interest be questioned.
Ditta pleaded not guilty and stated: &quot;If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to give information to Mr. Scarborough, I would not have waited 15 hours, I would have done it immediately.&quot;
But after the meeting, Senior Officer Lee Halstead of the Lancashire Police said: &quot;Mr Ditta went from being a criminal lawyer to a criminal as soon as he started buying drugs from organized crime.&quot;
His addiction to cocaine left him hopelessly compromised and vulnerable to the targets of the main members of the criminal gangs, who tasked him with obtaining valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must uphold the highest standards of professional ethics and inspire public trust and confidence.
Mr. Ditta betrayed this trust and tried to hide behind his profession.
Mr. Ditt was being investigated by the Lancashire Serious Organized Crime Unit, which had already secured a conviction for him on three counts of possession of cocaine and now also on obstruction of justice, demonstrating our commitment to getting the perpetrators justly punished.
Let this case serve as a warning to criminals that no one is beyond the reach of the law.
We will find you and bring you to justice.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years after pleading guilty to conspiracy to supply heroin, cocaine and marijuana.
Another 35 people involved in the fraud were sentenced in total to 153 years for drug-related crimes.
On his website, Ditta hosted a Q&amp;A in which he says his dream job is a lawyer representing death row clients in America, his ideal dinner companion is Muhammad Ali, and his job motivation is inequality .
Jet makers feud over seat width when big orders are at stake
A fierce dispute has erupted between leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of long-haul tourist class seats, setting the tone for a bitter confrontation at the Dubai Air Show this month.
The controversy revolves around the width of the seats provided on long-haul flights to economy passengers, whose interests are not always at the forefront of airlines, with the amount of space allocated to them playing a key role in the efficiency claims of the latest aircraft offered by Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
Airbus this week called for an industry standard that would require a seat width of at least 18 inches (46 cm) in economy class cabins, but its main US rival Boeing says it&#39;s up to airlines to decide.
The controversy comes at a time when aircraft manufacturers compete to sell ever larger versions of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft, with potentially record orders expected at the Nov. 17-21 event.
The layout of the rear of the aircraft—especially whether 9 or 10 people sit abreast—is central to the cost-effectiveness claims of new &quot;mini-airbus&quot; designs.
Boeing says its updated 777X will seat 406 people, based on economy class seats over 17 inches wide, with 10 in each row.
Airbus says a competing version of its A350 will carry 350 people in economy class in 18-inch-wide seats arranged 9 abreast.
Aircraft giants often trade blows on technical issues through advertisements in the professional press.
And now Airbus is speaking directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to take the lead with over 100 orders.
She recently demonstrated what the start of a new advertising war could be like by showing financiers a slide of three people huddled together in a restaurant titled &quot;Would you agree to this?&quot;
“Boeing offers long-haul flights on seats that are narrower than regional turboprops,” said Airbus head of sales John Leahy.
People put on weight as diets change, but airplane seats haven&#39;t changed dramatically.
Between the early 1970s, when the wide-body Boeing 747 set the standard for modern long-haul travel, and the turn of the century, the weight of the average American male aged 40 to 49 increased by 10 percent, according to the US Department of Health.
The waist circumference of the average 21st century American male is 39.7 inches, according to US Health Service statistics.
Airbus claims its competitor is sticking to the seating concept of the 1950s, when the average waistline of those recently dubbed the &quot;jet public&quot; was narrower.
Airbus says it has commissioned a study showing that an extra inch in seat width improves sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing disputes Airbus&#39;s seat size figures and says manufacturers shouldn&#39;t get involved in decisions about how airlines balance fares and amenities.
According to her, studies show that the comfort of the cabin depends not only on the width of the seat.
“It really comes down to giving airlines the choice and the ability to do what they think they need to do to be successful,” said Boeing cabin specialist Kent Craver.
They do not want us to decide for them what will bring them profit.
They know their business better than anyone else.
For passengers, the issue is more space on the sides, but for suppliers this is increasingly becoming a factor that can affect profits.
Behind the dispute is a race for aircraft orders worth at least $700 billion at list prices in the coming decades, enough to change the balance between US and European exports.
As Reuters first reported in July, the seating arrangement is exactly what is fueling the rivalry in the battle between the latest jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim a 20 percent improvement in profitability per seat in their latest twin-engine long-haul models compared to the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 777-300ER.
Boeing&#39;s performance claims are based in part on a comparison of the 777X&#39;s 10-seat rows with the original 777&#39;s 9-seat row layout.
The unit cost gain is reduced when compared to the 10-seat layout currently in use.
“The reason Boeing is doing this is to cram in more seats and make their aircraft more competitive with our designs,” said Kevin Keniston, head of passenger comfort for Airbus Europe.
On the other hand, analysts say full 10-seat rows for existing 777s indicate that many passengers prefer tighter seating, which could go hand in hand with lower fares.
“Eighteen-inch-wide seats would be ideal for passengers, but the reality is that, commercially, the Airbus proposal is driven by the threat of the 777,” said cabin interior designer Mary Kirby, founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not supply seats, but do offer a catalog of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
Traveling jet salesmen even carry tape measures with them to test competing layouts.
While touting comfort, all manufacturers also offer very dense aircraft for low-cost airlines and regional travel.
Airbus is offering the A350 with 10-seat rows but says it hasn&#39;t sold one yet.
Until recently, Airbus has emphasized the need for additional cabin modifications by offering wider aisle seats on some of its aircraft.
Without the backing of the only other manufacturer of large modern aircraft, experts say, her call for a new industry standard is unlikely to take off, but could detract from the wave of 777X sales.
