Security concerns in Mozambique rise as powerful people clash
Beneath a staring down statue of Samora Machel, Mozambique&#39;s founding president, thousands of people gathered in downtown Maputo to chant peace in one of the rare demonstrations here.
“We want the return of peace; we want stability,” said Vanessa de Susa, chief executive of the investment firm.
Fearing for the future of her country, she changed from her business suit to a T-shirt emblazoned with the words &quot;We demand security&quot; in Portuguese and joined the crowd at the capital&#39;s Independence Square on Thursday.
For two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, some of the most violent clashes since the armistice more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a notorious insurgency supported first by the white Rhodesian authorities and later by the apartheid-era South African government as part of an effort to destabilize the country&#39;s independent government.
After the 1992 armistice, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to slide back into full-blown conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and local residents nervous.
The stakes are high for a booming economy as the discovery of vast offshore gas and coal reserves in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from the likes of Rio Tinto, Vale of Brazil, Eni of Italy and Anadarko of the United States .
The ruling Frelimo party, the leading political force since 1975, and the Renamo party blame each other for the tension.
The Renamo Party claims that the government was the instigator of the latest clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofala, a traditional stronghold of Renamo, on October 17th.
Attacks on the former rebels then escalated when government troops attacked Renamo bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group&#39;s leader, Renamo&#39;s spokesman Fernando Mazanga told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating the clashes, accusing the party of attacking the soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza attempted to allay fears of instability.
Guebuza told AFP, the French news agency, on Wednesday that Mr Dhlakama felt like a &quot;loser&quot; who wanted to use &quot;whatever was left of his strength to try and prove that he could impose his own decisions on the government.&quot;
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist they want to avoid war.
However, fears grew after reports that Mazanga had announced Renamo&#39;s rejection of the 1992 peace deal.
He told the Financial Times that he was referring to Frelimo&#39;s non-compliance with the agreement.
“Our goal is to return to negotiations, but in all seriousness,” Masanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have done little to ease tensions that have been intensified by a series of clashes this year.
“These are two powerful men (Guebuza and Dhlakama) head-on,” said Joseph Hanlon, an Open University lecturer and expert on Mozambique.
Neither is a good negotiator and neither is willing to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo&#39;s party, which is pushing for electoral reforms, has already said it will boycott municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators have interpreted this pressure as an attempt by the weakened movement to win concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
Renamo&#39;s share of the vote has been declining since 1992, while a new party, the Democratic Movement of Mozambique (MDM), founded by a former Renamo member, is expected to improve in this election.
Mr Mazanga says Mr Guebuza, who is due to step down next year when his second term ends, wants to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn’t want multi-party democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to leave the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is not clear what capabilities Renamo has, but she has already carried out devastating and swift attacks on police stations and vehicles on a key north-south highway.
Most of the skirmishes took place in Sofala province, which is several hundred kilometers north of Maputo but includes Beira, a port that mining companies including Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended rail use for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railroad.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat this threat.
The Renamo party wanted to &quot;warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique,&quot; Mazanga said.
Instability has heightened dissatisfaction with the government, and many people also worry about corruption, the slow pace of development and the recent increase in kidnappings, says Fernando Lima, head of independent media company Mediacoop.
“People think that the responsibility for the future of the country lies with the government and the president, who should find a solution to these problems,” he says.
Omar Sultuan, a demonstrator, said people just want stability.
“No one cares about either Renamo or Frelimo, they just want peace to resume, they want free access to the roads,” he said.
Rules for the use of electronic devices on aircraft in Australia will remain in effect for the time being
Australian airline passengers will continue to be required to turn off their tablets and smartphones during takeoff and landing, despite measures in the US to ease regulations on these devices.
The US Federal Aviation Administration has allowed US carriers to change their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos, or play games on their devices during takeoff and landing, as long as they remain in Airplane Mode.
Passengers can already do this during the main part of the flight, but many are annoyed that they do not have access to their e-books during takeoff and landing.
Australian carriers are considering the decision, which has required US airlines to do a huge amount of work to meet the new requirements, but have indicated they have no plans to change their procedures in the near future.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also noted that they are reviewing the application, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices during critical phases of flight are still in place in Australia.
&quot;The Civil Aviation Safety Authority does not currently have specific rules governing the use of electronic devices in aircraft,&quot; it said.
This issue is governed by rules that require air carriers to maintain security at all times, and passengers to follow the safety rules communicated to them by crew members.
Virgin, which has already been in discussions with the Aviation Safety Authority to expand the use of its Wi-Fi inflight entertainment system, was not opposed to the changes, but said it would follow the regulator&#39;s guidance.
“We would welcome the Civil Aviation Safety Authority&#39;s consideration of allowing the use of electronic devices, because we really think that this will improve the customer experience now that it (in-flight wireless entertainment system) is on our aircraft,” a spokesman said. .
Qantas said it will adhere to the current rules.
“Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during takeoff and landing, and we do not plan to change it anytime soon,” she said.
The FAA regulation applies to US airlines.
However, we are always interested in regulatory changes that could benefit passengers, and we will certainly look into the FAA&#39;s decision and the reasons behind it.
For US carriers, the impact of the ruling will vary from airline to airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will need to prove that their aircraft are immune to radio interference from mobile devices, as well as review manuals, training materials, carry-on baggage allowances and passenger instructions.
“Once an airline has tested and validated the immunity of its fleet, it may allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-readers and smartphones at any altitude,” the FAA said.
In rare cases of poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off their devices during boarding.
