Scientists have shed light on how a dog&#39;s tail movements are related to its mood.
Earlier research has shown that contented dogs wag their tails to the right (from the dog&#39;s point of view), while anxious dogs wag their tails predominantly to the left.
But now scientists say other members of the canine family can notice and respond to these subtle differences in tail wagging.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at Trent University, says: &quot;It is well known that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in generating triggers that evoke positive or negative emotions.&quot;
Here we tried to look at this in other species as well.
He added that just like in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the versatile tail wagging of other dogs, the researchers observed the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
We will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: &quot;We showed the dogs videos of dogs - either naturalistic versions or a silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and point the tail more to the left or to the right.&quot;
When the animals saw the otherwise expressionless dog move its tail to the right (from the point of view of the wagging dog), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning predominantly to the left (again from the point of view of a wagging dog), their heart rate increased and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they should and should not be concerned about.
He remarks, “If there are multiple encounters with other dogs and often their tail wagging to one side is associated with more friendly behavior and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts based on that experience.”
The researchers say these results could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal&#39;s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol School of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to test whether left and right sides make a difference in dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists at Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when facing an aggressive dog and to the right when facing a contented dog.
And in another paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs approached the robot dog more often when its tail wagged to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming alarmed—the opposite behavior of the Italian study.”
He said the differences could be because the dogs in the various studies didn&#39;t fully perceive the animals in the movies or the robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is ample evidence in various mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details remain to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes point one way and sometimes the other.
