Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of CNN&#39;s 10 main characters of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to be CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue their outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father come back to life and fall back into unconsciousness, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jameef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaounde, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma, which reminded of itself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” Georges Bwelle said.
If we had money, we would take him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father to crowded clinics and hospitals for years, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
“It&#39;s not easy,” Bwelle said.
- You can leave home at 5 in the morning, run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation has not changed much since Father Bwelle passed away in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people in Cameroon.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor for every 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health care spending is privately owned.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
“And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and so many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He became a physician himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded ASCOVIME, a non-profit organization that organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others pack into wagons, tie medical supplies to the roofs, and drive across rough terrain to visit villages in need.
They are not always lucky.
More than once they had to push cars through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like real heroes: it&#39;s a celebration of song and dance and the finest accommodations the locals have to offer.
The free medical care in these villages is truly something to celebrate, and Bwelle, with his big smile and boundless energy, is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We host 500 people on each trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the area within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can get crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates—documents needed for school that many poor families simply can&#39;t afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in a school building, municipality or home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to light the operating room and sanitize equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
This is an unbearable pace, but the purposefulness of the brigade is usually helped to maintain the village musicians.
“They beat drums all night to keep us awake and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the crew members head back to town, tired but proud of their work.
This group of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students have performed 700 free surgeries in the past year and they know their help can make a huge difference to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia surgery he received would allow him to work again.
“This will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these weekend clinical appointments and hospital work as a surgeon, Bwelle also works nights in private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second job that he says provides 60% of his nonprofit&#39;s funding; the remaining funds are covered by private donations.
&quot;I don&#39;t even know when he sleeps,&quot; said Cathy O&#39;Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer with Bwelle&#39;s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses like O&#39;Malley coming from the US and Europe to join Bwell in his mission, this is a practice opportunity they would never have at home.
“We were able to assist in surgeries where we helped remove bloodstains or hold instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O&#39;Malley said.
As a sophomore, you would never get that opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive in Yaoundé, Bwelle pays for their food, transportation and education.
&quot;He&#39;s a hero, no doubt about it,&quot; O&#39;Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
