Goldman Sachs warns of risks for the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks to the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia - consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payments on unsecured consumer loans and massive layoffs of workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather the structure of that growth.
Recently, it has been entirely driven by consumption, which is almost not slowing down,&quot; said Clemens Grafe, chief economist for Russia at Goldman Sachs, presenting yesterday the investment bank&#39;s quarterly report on the Russian economy.
Now the nominal growth of wages in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation at 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so, most likely, they will start optimizing personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - Mr. Grafe explained.
The companies faced shrinking profitability.
If it does not grow, it could lead to layoffs and rising unemployment.
Russian business cannot help raising salaries, comments Vladimir Pantyushin, chief economist at Barclays Capital for Russia and the CIS.
Unemployment near historical lows, competition for workers is high.
Employers have to raise salaries in order to lure employees from outside or keep current ones.
Consumption in Russia is also supported by a very rapid growth in consumer lending.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to the extremely high interest rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the country&#39;s economy.
&quot;We did not see any benefit for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, the money does not disperse throughout the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,&quot; the economist said.
But the problem is different - Goldman Sachs expects an increase in delinquency on unsecured loans.
They are taken mostly by poor people who have nothing to provide in security.
The interest rates on these loans are high.
As a result, they are often not returned,&quot; Grafe noted.
Therefore, the second threat to economic growth in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payments on unsecured loans.
Vasily Solodkov, director of the HSE Banking Institute, is already seeing signs of a looming banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, not having access to cheap resources, which state-owned banks have, were forced to attract funds from the population at high interest rates.
In response, state-owned banks went on the warpath and began to reduce lending rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rates, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state-owned banks do not give up dumping, Russia is facing a full-fledged banking crisis, Vasily Solodkov believes.
The economist considers the deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks as a harbinger of a massive collapse.
&quot;State-owned banks themselves will not cope with such a situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis,&quot; the head of the institute warns.
But consumption growth will slow down even without a crisis of non-payments, according to the investment bank, due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and the military, which is included in the current version of the draft budget.
Part of the impact on consumption will be mitigated by freezing the tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a result, lower inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see the reference), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is sure.
Vladimir Pantyushin from Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
&quot;The main risk is still the fall in the price of oil,&quot; he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to decline when the cost of oil is below 90 dollars per barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks have begun to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting,&quot; said Clemens Grafe.
The interest rate policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
&quot;For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes,&quot; Clemens Grafe assessed.
Banks use the money received at auctions of the Central Bank not for lending to the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate drops, the exchange rate immediately changes, which means that the funds are trying to go to speculation against the ruble.
&quot;Sooner or later, the Central Bank will realize that this strategy is not working,&quot; Mr. Grafe said and recalled that the state plans to float the ruble by the end of 2015.
