Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could take away the pleasure of smoking cigarettes.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before human trials can begin, which will take several years, but Prof Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said early results are encouraging.
“We very much hope that this vaccine strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying every method available on the market today, only to find that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to be overcome with these modern remedies.” Professor Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry the genetic information for the production of anti-nicotinic antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
The antibodies track down any nicotine molecules in the bloodstream, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
In tests, vaccinated mice that were subsequently given nicotine continued their normal activities.
And the mice that weren&#39;t given the vaccine &quot;relaxed,&quot; a sign that nicotine was reaching their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
To keep antibody levels high, injections had to be given so frequently that they were both expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they have the urge to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to stop smoking.
&quot;They will know that if they start smoking again, they won&#39;t enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that might help them kick the habit,&quot; he said.
