Politicians have expressed concern that the EU lacks certain IT and Internet capabilities and opined that it should try to reduce its dependence on the US.
Businessmen are skeptical about this.
Someone in the German parliament says we should create a German Google.
I can only close my eyes and slowly open them again...
&quot;That&#39;s not an option,&quot; says Gasso Plattner, president of German business software provider SAP.
If there is a need for a powerful European IT industry, it should not have been allowed to die more than 20 years ago.
Everything is subsidized in Germany: from coal to cars to farmers.
Everything except the IT industry.
Yet the reach and sophistication of US spying agencies made famous by Snowden&#39;s revelations came as a shock to some companies that had previously thought that China was the biggest risk of surveillance.
A big shift is taking place in the cloud, where European business leaders have become more aware that data stored in the US is in the same jurisdiction and therefore potentially vulnerable.
About 10 percent of non-U.S. members have abandoned plans to use a U.S.-based cloud provider after the US data mining program Prism was exposed, according to research by the Cloud Security Alliance trade association.
Jim Snabe, one of the chief executives of SAP, said: &quot;We see consumers asking a new question that did not arise a year ago, namely: where is my data stored and can you guarantee that it will physically remain in this jurisdiction.&quot;
Many German leaders argue that the latest reports are just confirmation of what they already knew: powerful states want to steal their most valuable secrets, and therefore this data must be protected at all costs.
The fact that economic espionage is taking place is not surprising.
It has always been there.
