Agency &quot;Rosbalt&quot; was deprived of the status of the media for obscene language
On October 31, the Moscow City Court ruled to invalidate the registration license of the Rosbalt agency, writes Lenta.
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of its media status for systematic and gross violations of the media law.
During the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, in fact, denying the publication the right to put forward counterarguments.
What is &quot;Rosbalt&quot;
CJSC Information Agency Rosbalt was founded in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In subsequent years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional divisions.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has been developing and functioning as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency&#39;s exclusive publications was (and still is) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talk about the closeness of the publication to law enforcement agencies continued throughout the existence of the agency.
Along with the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive database of sources in various departments, such assumptions were also supported by the fact that Natalya Chaplina, the wife of Viktor Cherkesov, was at the head of the project.
At the same time, the role of Chaplina in the leadership of Rosbalt is not completely clear: most often she is called the &quot;project manager&quot;.
The director general of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently Rosbalt has not appeared in the ratings of the federal media - neither in terms of citation, nor in terms of audience.
In October, the agency ranked 25th in the ranking of Russian media website traffic according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials over the past five months are notes about the helplessness of the Kremlin in relations with Ukraine, the death of the lead singer of the King and the Shut group, and pogroms in the capital Biryulyovo.
The conflict between Rosbalt and Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on the media came into force, prohibiting journalists from using obscene language.
The agency found prohibited vocabulary in two videos published on the agency&#39;s website (&quot;Dzhigit from Krasnodar&quot; and &quot;Pussy Riot defiled oil rigs&quot;).
The rest of the story is described differently by the parties.
Roskomnadzor, on the basis of the discovered video materials, accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the media law and filed a lawsuit demanding that the agency&#39;s license be revoked.
Rosbalt stated that the claims of the department were unlawful: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the swear words in them were disguised, and thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed the claims of Roskomnadzor in the world court - and when on October 22, 2013 the Moscow City Court accepted the claim of Roskomnadzor, consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, already on the 25th, the justice of the peace ruled not in favor of Rosbalt: editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code of administrative offenses and fined 20,000 rubles - 10,000 rubles for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if we abandon the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court ruled to invalidate Rosbalt&#39;s registration certificate, effectively depriving the agency of its media status.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by the deputies of the State Duma (an application addressed to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov was signed on October 10 by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Council for Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov spoke about the illegality of closing the publication.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that the matter would not come to revocation of the license.
The trial of Rosbalt showed that under whose jurisdiction it is safer for the media to be in Russia today is a big question.
