Scientists found that the Foxp2 gene was disrupted in family members, but how it performs its function remained unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that Foxp2 performs at least part of its function as a stimulator of the formation of new synapses in a region of the brain associated with the formation of speech.
He does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 turned out to be one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, while Foxp2 affects its activity only.
The fact that SRPX2 does affect vocalization was confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the gene activity was artificially reduced in animals, they screamed less when separated from their mother.
If the gene activity was restored, the frequency of emitted sounds was also restored.
An association with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself has also been shown previously in mice.
Animals injected with a human copy of the gene squeaked more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
Until now, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, accordingly, SRPX2 controlled by it, is connected with purely &quot;mechanical&quot; properties of sound production or more subtle processes.
