General Motors Co. is recalling nearly 19,000 brand-new 2014 Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra pickup trucks to address issues with manual seatback reclining, pursuant to a notice from US motor vehicle safety regulators introduced Friday.
On some of the pickups, the front seats may have a defect in the backrest tilt mechanism.
As a result, seat backs do not meet federal motor vehicle safety head restraint standards.
“In the event of a rear impact, the head restraint may not adequately protect the driver and passengers, increasing the risk of injury,” according to a notice posted on the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration website.
The recalled models were manufactured between August 1 and September 10.
GM&#39;s pickup truck launch began in June and represents the most important vehicle launch for the leading American automaker since its 2009 bankruptcy restructuring.
GM informed pickup truck owners of the defect in the first half of October.
The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration was unable to review the notice to owners due to a 16-day government shutdown that dampened growth in car sales in October.
Sales of the Silverado and Sierra pickups, which were redesigned for the 2014 lineup, rose about 20 percent during the first 10 months of this year, GM said Friday.
In October, GM sold 42,660 Silverado pickups and 16,503 Sierra pickups.
Shares of GM on the New York Stock Exchange on Friday afternoon rose 1.4 percent to $37.47.
