Snowden ready to &#39;cooperate&#39; with Germany on US intelligence issue
Edward Snowden, a US intelligence whistleblower, has said he is willing to travel to Berlin to testify before the German parliament if the US National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander fail to answer questions about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Ströbele met with Mr Snowden in Russia, where he has been granted asylum, on Thursday to discuss his testimony in Germany.
The letter from Mr Snowden, which the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: “Although the result of my efforts has been clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as treason and seeks to criminalize political speech with criminal charges that offer no protection.” .
However, telling the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Mr. Snowden said he believes the support of the international community can convince the US government to drop the criminal charges against him.
Charges filed by the US Department of Justice include espionage and theft of government property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany&#39;s interior minister, told Zeit Online: &quot;If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make it possible.&quot;
Relations between the US and Germany have become tense after allegations that the NSA was tapping Chancellor Angela Merkel&#39;s phone.
Thomas Opperman, the MP who chairs the parliamentary group overseeing the intelligence service, said that if there was an opportunity to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness &quot;without endangering him and completely destroying relations with the US,&quot; it should be seized.
Mr Ströbele, an MP from the German Green Party, posted a photo of himself with Mr Snowden on his Twitter.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Ströbele said that according to a lawyer for the former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden could not return to Russia if he left.
If Mr Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would need assurances that he would be &quot;safe&quot; there, the MP said.
Mr Snowden said in his letter that he faced a &quot;tough and persistent&quot; campaign of harassment that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was encouraged by the worldwide reaction to &quot;his political statements&quot;.
Citizens around the world, as well as high-ranking officials - including in the United States - found the exposure of an uncontrolled system of pervasive surveillance beneficial to society.
The letter contains an offer to cooperate with the German authorities &quot;when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved.&quot;
