This test, if passed, would apply under criteria designed to prevent Class 457 visas from being used to fill unskilled positions or as a loophole to move family and friends to Australia.
The government&#39;s discussion paper was released today as former Labor MP Maxine McKue criticized the government&#39;s rhetoric regarding foreign workers, saying it could offend Australia&#39;s neighbors.
“The &#39;Foreigners back of the line&#39; and &#39;Australians work first&#39; rants represent a very nasty throwback to the days when unions demanded a secure labor market,” she told the Australia India Institute today.
Historically, this meant that it was white labor that needed to be protected - and if some in the region saw echoes of this historical artifact, I would not be surprised.
The discussion paper outlines 12 measures previously considered by former Immigration Secretary Chris Bowen.
Immigration Minister Brendan O&#39;Connor, who was in Sri Lanka yesterday where he is meeting with officials about human smuggling, has already made five of the recommended changes and the rest are under consideration.
If the criteria for &quot;authenticity&quot; are adopted, the visa applicant could be examined as to whether &quot;the candidacy is genuine in circumstances where the candidate is a relative or close acquaintance of the owner or a person involved in the financing of the enterprise&quot;.
Businesses may also be required to report the number of subclass 457 visa holders, as previously businesses that intended to sponsor a small number of workers then hired hundreds.
