In the United States, it will be possible to use mobile phones during takeoff and landing of the aircraft
New rules for the safe use of mobile devices during takeoff and landing of an airliner have been approved in the United States, the BBC reports.
American airlines are expected to allow passengers to use smartphones and tablets throughout their flight, with the new rules coming into effect by the end of 2013.
However, Internet connection to receive and send e-mail will be prohibited during flights below 3 kilometers.
Due to the risk of interference from aircraft radio equipment, cellular voice communications will continue to be banned.
Thus, passengers on flights will be allowed to read e-books, play games on tablets and other gadgets, and watch videos during domestic and international flights.
Before the rules are adopted, airlines will be required to check the safety of the use of electronic devices throughout the flight.
In addition, airlines will have to convince the US Federal Aviation Administration that they will be able to cope with the alleged impact of mobiles on aircraft equipment and aircraft controls.
According to the source, following the example of the United States, Britain may also be reviewing the current rules for the use of electronic devices in flights.
