An earthquake of magnitude 6.6 occurred on Thursday, October 31, near the city of Coquimbo in central Chile, reports Reuters.
The source of the earthquake was in the ocean at a depth of 10.7 kilometers and at a distance of 54 kilometers southwest of the city, according to the website of the US Geological Survey (USGS).
The aftershocks were recorded at 20:03 local time (3:03 November 1 Moscow time).
No casualties or damage caused by the tremors have yet been reported.
Recall that Chile is located in one of the most seismically active regions of the Earth, so earthquakes of various strengths are not uncommon there.
One of the most serious happened in 2010.
Then an earthquake of magnitude 8.8 and the tsunami caused by it led to the death of more than 550 people in Chile and the destruction of 220,000 buildings.
In addition, the most powerful earthquake in recent history occurred in Chile: in 1960, a magnitude of 9.5 was recorded there.
More than 5,000 people died as a result of that natural disaster.
