Syria destroyed chemical weapons equipment
Syria has destroyed all of its declared chemical weapons production capacity, the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons has acknowledged.
Damascus completed this first stage of disarmament a day before the deadline.
Before November 1, Syria was supposed to destroy production and other auxiliary facilities intended for the preparation of chemical warfare agents for use, the BBC reports.
The destruction of the stocks of poisonous substances themselves or their chemical components should be completed by mid-2014.
According to the OPCW representative, the poisonous substances are currently in sealed storage facilities.
International inspectors went to Syria after more than 1,400 people were killed in a chemical attack on the outskirts of Damascus on August 21, according to the United States.
The main task of the inspectors was not to waste time - not to allow the Syrian authorities to produce more chemical weapons - and to destroy the infrastructure for mixing chemicals and reloading ammunition.
These production facilities will now be closely monitored to prevent them from being repaired.
The next milestone is mid-November: by this time, the OPCW and the Syrians should agree on a detailed plan for the destruction of already existing stockpiles of toxic substances.
There are many questions here.
Where will they be destroyed?
Who will provide the equipment for this?
All Syrian statements will be carefully checked by Western intelligence services.
They will readily advise inspectors on new sites to check if there is any reason to suspect that Damascus is not completely outspoken.
The US believes that this shelling was carried out by regular troops.
Syria and Russia insist that this is the work of the Syrian rebels.
The world community demanded from the Syrian leadership - in accordance with the agreement reached through the mediation of Russia - to destroy or disable all facilities for the production of shells, poison gases and liquids and for filling shells with these substances.
Now that this stage has been passed, the next step should be to destroy the Syrian army&#39;s existing chemical weapons.
It is estimated that this arsenal could contain more than 1,000 tons of nerve agents, blister mustard gas and other banned chemicals stored in dozens of different locations.
To destroy it, it is necessary that the OPCW and the Syrian authorities first agree on a timetable of action - two weeks are allotted for this.
OPCW field operations chief Jerry Smith told the BBC that his inspectors &quot;personally oversaw the destruction of equipment.&quot;
&quot;They don&#39;t have the capacity to continue producing or blending chemical weapons now,&quot; he said.
The OPCW said in a statement that inspectors visited 21 of the 23 sites in Syria and found that the factories for the production of shells and poisonous substances were either destroyed or rendered unusable.
The remaining two sites are too dangerous to be inspected there, the document says, but the equipment from there was transported and checked by OPCW specialists.
Smith said the process of destroying the chemical weapons infrastructure was &quot;particularly challenging&quot; because of the ongoing conflict.
In early October, the OPCW received the Nobel Peace Prize, but, according to Smith, the inspectors have not yet found time to celebrate this - they were too busy with work.
George Kerevan: Break with Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland will have to join the pan-European free movement area as a condition of EU membership.
It&#39;s time for stories about passport control at Berwick and the barbed-wire border along Hadrian&#39;s Wall.
It is true that Strathclyde pointed to the possible economic benefits of freer movement throughout the rest of Europe, although - predictably - this did not make headlines.
Nor did anyone point out that EU member states spend a lot of time twisting their formal rules to their advantage.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for what it really wanted from the Scots.
So it&#39;s not a worthy story.
And so old that it has turned into a fossil: the first time I heard the “duck” that “independence means passport control” was at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting point lost in the retelling of the old tale.
Why should an independent Scotland take orders from Europe at all?
Why change the yoke of London for the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here&#39;s the real European news: The great post-war plan to unify Europe has finally stalled.
With the Eurocrisis, the Europe project is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or for the abolition of the euro as the single currency are gaining momentum.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party - founded just this year - came out of nowhere and received almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus essentially ousting the Free Democrats (an analogue of our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag. .
There has always been internal opposition to the plan for a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has been a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the retention of the single currency, have led many people to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are operating with excessive budget deficits - this was true only for Greece.
In fact, the eurosystem has blocked its members from exchange rates favorable to German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself at a disadvantage in terms of production capabilities in comparison with Germany.
The only saving grace is to cut salaries and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems is a deeper problem with Europe&#39;s productive capacity.
As a result of Brussels&#39; green energy package - a cipher for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as in the United States.
These are paralyzingly unfavorable price conditions, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
No amount of global wage freezes will stop the crushing victory of cheap US shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, revolt is brewing, especially in France, once the most ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving France&#39;s shattered economy in distress.
The result is that Marine Le Pen&#39;s right-wing, anti-EU National Front party has just won a decisive by-election, dropping the ruling Socialist party to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the vote, a timely warning to British Labor not to assume that a split on the right will automatically ripple in favor of the left.
What is Le Pen doing with his newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use next year&#39;s EU elections to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If, as is very likely, anti-EU parties gain support in these elections, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: soon the growing anti-EU and anti-single currency sentiment in Europe will merge to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something of the vague &quot;Europe of (sovereign) nations&quot; that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several dependent economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
My guess is that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
However, Washington&#39;s growing interest in the Pacific points to the possibility that the UK will be left behind in the cold of the Atlantic.
Where does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region of (essentially) Little Anglia.
Or we can protect our own economic interests, which means, among other things, send Berlin and Brussels to hell.
