Early puberty: aging earlier
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers, studies show.
Physical changes don&#39;t mean puberty is near
No evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame
Experts believe the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children&#39;s health and family issues.
Should a mother be alarmed if her daughter begins to develop breast buds and pubic hair at age 7 or 8?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics&#39; annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are fairly common among American girls and represent the new normal.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring my parents — it usually doesn’t mean going full puberty quickly,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair, and body odor appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the median age is 12.5, down from 12.75 in 1970.
&quot;Once breasts begin to develop, it&#39;s at least two to three years before menarche,&quot; said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of Early Puberty in Girls: How to Cope with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
There is debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered &quot;premature&quot; when breast augmentation is accompanied by a dramatic increase in height before 8 years of age.
In most cases, the process will slow down or pause - this is something that the pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression may warrant testing by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to stunted growth and short stature in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child&#39;s age, developmental level, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is wary of medication, but admits that &quot;puberty suppression can mitigate behavioral problems and girls&#39; feelings of being different from their peers.&quot;
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply don&#39;t want their very young daughters to menstruate.
&quot;They&#39;re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they&#39;ll handle hygiene issues,&quot; Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruating at age 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school frightened and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many publicized theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys, like girls, experience puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the premise that carries the most weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped lead a study of girls aged 6 to 9 that links body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other data support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are various explanations.
Around the world, everything from economic conditions and climate to genes seems to influence early puberty.
Another mystery: although boys develop facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency to complete early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other clinicians attending the AAP conference have confirmed the complexity of this topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and toddlers.
&quot;We have to be careful about how we define true puberty,&quot; said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children&#39;s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get guidance from a pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This could mean an earlier-than-expected conversation,” Kaplowitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need reassurance that even when it happens early, this process is a normal part of life.
