Indeed, demand in various parts of Southeast Asia - where household debt is rising - is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its deal, became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
A jewelry-backed loan is not just a quick way to get money (S$1,300 in Ms. Amirthalinga&#39;s case), but almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% - just above the 15.4% offered at a branch of United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require a credit check or proof of salary and can make loans faster than banks.
Therefore, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel pressure from rising living costs and rapidly rising household and consumer debt.
After five years of solid growth following the global financial crisis and cheap credit fueled by loose monetary policy in the advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to offset declining incomes as their economies slow down.
This week, Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s, a ratings agency, cited an increase in family leverage, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It stated that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest household debt-to-gross domestic product ratios in Asia.
