“The bottom line is that as prices rise, people in the middle and bottom [of the income scale] will look for ways to supplement their income wherever they can,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Record high gold prices over the past two years have exacerbated the rush for people to pawn their personal belongings as they seize the opportunity to cash in on their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70% of the items pawned in the city-state&#39;s 200 pawn shops are gold items.
People say, &quot;The price of gold looks good, let&#39;s pawn grandma&#39;s gold chain and get it back next month.&quot;
In Thailand, the largest pawnshop operator EasyMoney has seen a rise in the number of customers using its branches in recent months, up to 20%.
