The company will finance the expansion using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week from a public offering on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have drawn fire for high interest rates, Ms Yeah says the pawnshop not only offers cheaper rates than other lenders, it also doesn&#39;t increase debt directly.
“Clients are pledging items they already own, and monetizing personal assets does not increase household debt,” she says.
Mortgages are gaining more and more public acceptance as a means of obtaining short-term, secured financing.
