Do you have a black box in your car?
As American road planners scramble to raise money to fix the crumbling highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in the little black box tucked neatly into your car&#39;s dashboard.
These devices, which track every mile a motorist drives and relay that information to officials, are at the center of a controversial effort by Washington and state planners to modernize America&#39;s outdated highway funding system.
The normally dull arena of highway planning has unexpectedly generated intense debate and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use little boxes to keep track of how many miles you drive, and perhaps even where you drive them, and then use that information when compiling tax bills.
