This is really necessary for our country.
“This is not an issue where we can have a choice,” said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Association of Southern California Governments, which is preparing plans for the state to begin tracking the miles driven by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay these taxes.
The technology for this already exists.
The need for this is exacerbated by the lack of funds from the Government&#39;s Highway Fund, funded by the taxes Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans no longer buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel more miles per gallon.
