&quot;The gas tax just can&#39;t be saved,&quot; said Lee Mannich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed 500 tracking devices on cars to test the mileage system.
“This will be the best alternative in the long run,” he said.
The nerds call it a pardon user fee.
Not surprisingly, the idea appeals to urban liberals, as taxes could change the way you travel to reduce traffic congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planners in California are eyeing the system as they develop strategies to meet the targets set by the state&#39;s ambitious climate change laws.
However, Rep. Bill Schuster (R-PA), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he, too, sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free marketers at the Reason Foundation are also thrilled to make drivers pay by the mile.
“This is not just a tax that will go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of political affairs at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
This movement is also supported by two former US Transportation Secretaries who, in 2011, called on Congress to move in the direction of mileage pay.
The US Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would involve about 10,000 vehicles.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal due to concerns from rural legislators representing voters who often have to travel many miles in their daily lives to get to work or the city.
Several states and cities, however, are pursuing this path on their own.
Enthusiasm is strongest in Oregon, which is recruiting 5,000 drivers to participate in the nation&#39;s largest pilot.
These drivers will soon be paying the state for driving miles instead of a gas tax.
In Nevada, a pilot project has already been completed.
In New York it is considered.
Illinois is testing it on a limited basis with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes transportation departments from 17 east coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is exploring how they can make these changes.
This concept has not received general acceptance.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer vehicles were recently fitted with the devices, drivers were concerned that the government might track their every move.
&quot;Concerns about &#39;big brother&#39; and things like that are a big problem,&quot; said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn&#39;t what people wanted.
As the tests were under way, the Nevada branch of the American Civil Liberties Union warned on its website, &quot;It will not be difficult to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices.&quot;
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of several states in the arduous search for low-cost technology that would allow state officials to keep track of miles driven by a car, but without information about place and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more relaxed.
The search for this technology led some agencies in the state to a small, young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, this company was not involved in assisting in the collection of state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market for a form of auto insurance in which drivers pay based on mileage.
But the devices she&#39;s testing appeal to road planners because they don&#39;t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information periodically downloaded via modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, chief executive of True Mileage.
There have been some big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they may choose to forego the device altogether, opting instead to pay a flat fee based on the average number of miles driven by all residents of the state.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to a wary public by making devices do more, not less.
In New York City, transit officials are aiming to develop a taxing device that would also accept parking meter payments, provide &quot;pay as you go&quot; insurance, and collect a pool of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Motorists will be attracted to participate by the benefit that is offered to them,” the urban design document says.
Some transportation system designers, however, are wondering if all the talk of mileage is just a huge distraction.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the failure of the Highway Trust by raising gasoline taxes.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on hybrid car drivers and others whose vehicles don&#39;t use much gasoline to pay their fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when all you have to do is take an aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the law and public relations commission.
If we do this, hundreds of millions of drivers will be worried about their privacy and a host of other things.
Pope Francis to name first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will ordain new cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time in his term on February 22, the Vatican announced Thursday.
The cardinals are the highest clergy in the Catholic Church after the pope, and it is they who elect the popes, so that Francis will appoint his first group of people who will ultimately be involved in choosing his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, after the cardinal reaches the age of 80, he can no longer take part in the election of the pope - this is the prerogative of a group of 120 &quot;cardinal electors&quot;.
In announcing the news, Vatican spokesman Father Federico Lombardi said that a meeting of all current cardinals, known as a consistory, would be held prior to the ordination ceremony.
&quot;Pope Francis has decided to announce in advance his decision to convene a consistory in February in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings with cardinals from around the world,&quot; Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinal electors is likely to drop by February.
He said that usually the pope names as many cardinals as necessary to bring the number of cardinal electors back to 120, and as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wishes.
Next year&#39;s consistory will be significant because it will be the first since Francis was elected in March this year, according to Valero.
At the moment there is a kind of bias in favor of Europe and especially in favor of Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from other regions of the world to restore balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they are represented by an insignificant number of cardinals.
They will also be the first chosen cardinals since Francis formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with seeking ways to reform the church.
In the past, dad decided everything on his own.
“Francis has now chosen eight cardinals to assist him,” Valero said.
He said it was &quot;quite possible&quot; that Francis would look to the cardinals for advice.
But we have not been in such a situation before - all this is a first for us.
Valero said that popes usually made cardinal bishops from large parishes, but Francis &quot;is full of surprises - so we don&#39;t know who he will name.&quot;
