Syria destroys its chemical weapons manufacturing facilities, watchdog says
Syria has destroyed major equipment for the production of chemical weapons and poison gas munitions, an international monitoring team said Thursday, as violent clashes raged in the north of the country, near one of the facilities believed to be storing toxic substances.
Also Thursday, a Syrian activist group said more than 120,000 people have been killed since the start of the country&#39;s civil war almost three years ago.
The statement of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons was made one day before
The November 1 deadline set by this Hague-based organization for Damascus to destroy or “make inoperable” all chemical weapons production facilities and mechanisms that allow chemicals to be mixed into poison gas and filled with munitions.
The completion of what is essentially the initial phase of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable that aims to destroy all of Damascus&#39;s chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of equipment means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 metric tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came during heavy fighting on Thursday in the city of Safira, which experts believe is a chemical weapons production facility and storage facility, according to the UK-based Syrian Advocacy Center for Human Rights.
An activist group that tracked casualties through a network of activists in Syria said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of that number, 61,067 were said to be civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, the group said, 29,954 are members of President Bashar al-Assad&#39;s armed forces, 18,678 are pro-government fighters and 187 are Lebanese Hezbollah fighters.
Also among the dead, the statement said, were 2,202 army defectors and about 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
According to a July 25 UN estimate, 100,000 have died in the conflict since March 2011.
This figure has not been updated since.
The conflict forced about 2 million people to flee the country.
Assad&#39;s troops have been fighting in Safira for weeks against insurgents, many of whom are linked to al-Qaeda groups.
The center said there were casualties on both sides on Thursday, but did not provide specific figures.
The fighting has highlighted the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors, spurred on by the tight deadlines of their mission to rid Syria of a toxic arsenal in the midst of an ongoing civil war.
The OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, said in a statement that its team was &quot;now satisfied that it has verified and seen destroyed all of Syria&#39;s declared critical production and blending/fueling equipment.&quot;
She added that &quot;no additional inspection activities are currently planned.&quot;
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work, visiting 21 of the 23 sites declared by Damascus.
They were unable to visit two sites due to security concerns, inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPCW said both sites were, according to Syria, &quot;abandoned and ... items of the chemical weapons program located there have been moved to other claimed sites that have been verified.&quot;
It was not immediately clear whether the site at Safira was one of two sites that OPCW inspectors were unable to visit.
Syria has submitted a plan for the total destruction of its chemical weapons, which is due to be approved next month by the OPCW&#39;s executive committee.
“I applaud the courage and bravery that you all have shown in carrying out the most difficult mission ever undertaken by this organization,” Ahmet Üzümcü, director general of the watchdog group, said in a comment released by the OPCW.
For the third year now, the civil war has pitted mostly Sunni Muslim rebels against the Assad government and its security forces, which are made up of members of his Alawite sect, an offshoot of Shia Islam.
As for other developments, Rami Abdurrahman, head of the center, said there was a massive explosion on Wednesday at an air defense facility in Syria&#39;s coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
