What will the construction of the transport hub in Moscow lead to
Every year, the city authorities promise to equip more and more transport interchange hubs (TPU).
Until 2020, it is planned to put into operation 255 transport hubs.
What the project actually turns into, our correspondent understood.
A couple of months ago, a construction fence appeared near the Smolenskaya metro station on the Arbatsko-Pokrovskaya line.
The inscription said that the arrangement of the transport hub was underway.
All this was very strange, since no land transport stops near Smolenskaya and, therefore, it is impossible to transfer to it.
To get to the nearest trolleybus stop on the Garden Ring, you need to overcome about 130 meters, including the ground crossing through Karmanitsky Lane.
Now at &quot;Smolenskaya&quot; almost everything is finished.
The flower stall disappeared, the newspaper stand was dismantled, and the asphalt in front of the entrance was replaced by paving stones.
That&#39;s the whole transport hub.
Transport interchange hubs are planar and capital, - explain in the press service of the capital&#39;s Department of Transport.
There are no capital transport hubs yet.
And planar ones involve the construction of parking lots, the withdrawal of retail facilities that interfere with the movement of passengers, the creation of small architectural forms and landscaping.
Actually, planar transport hubs are not even dealt with by transport workers, but by professional landscapers from the Department of Capital Repairs of the city of Moscow.
A transport hub is not necessarily a complex structure, explains Mikhail Blinkin, director of the Institute for Transport Economics and Transport Policy at the Higher School of Economics.
Sometimes a roof over your head and a scoreboard announcing the time of arrival of the transport is enough.
For example, a completely full-fledged plane transfer hub was recently opened near the Yasenevo metro station.
Even without sheds, but with intercepting parking lots and scoreboards indicating when the bus will come.
But in pursuit of quantity, officials write everything down to TPU.
Back in 2011, the mayor&#39;s office planned to build 151 hubs for everything, 59 of them with capital construction.
Now the plans until 2020 include as many as 255 transport hubs.
Of these, one and a half hundred promise to hand over this year.
Although the city has a program for the development of TPU, no quality criteria have been identified, - says Alexander Morozov, co-chairman of the public organization &quot;City and Transport&quot;.
They report on the number of objects, but the quality of the transplant at each of them often deteriorates.
According to the expert, there should be two criteria: firstly, a reduction in the transfer time, and secondly, convenience.
First of all, the ability to change the mode of transport without going out in the rain.
In Moscow, when arranging TPU, sometimes it turns out exactly the opposite.
A striking example of the VDNKh metro station.
Previously, suburban buses from the Yaroslavskoe highway came to the square in front of the main entrance to the All-Russian Exhibition Center.
Now their stops have been moved to the opposite side of Yaroslavl on Cosmonauts Street.
Further from the metro, much further from the monorail, but closer to residential buildings.
In vain that the residents did not want the bus station under the windows at all and complained to all possible authorities.
Somehow it didn’t work out right away with the capital transport hubs in Moscow.
The first of them began to be built about five years ago near the Planernaya metro station.
The project was intended to be exemplary.
And it really turned out to be an example of how a transfer hub, given at the mercy of investors, turns into a banal shopping center.
No, there are platforms for buses, a canopy so as not to walk from the subway in the rain, and three floors of parking lots.
True, the Khimki trolleybuses No. 202 and No. 203 were not given a place in the Moscow TPU in principle.
They were pushed away from the subway as strangers.
But there is more space for trade.
There are 32 shops for clothes alone, and in general there is almost everything - from pet supplies to a car dealership.
Well, in fact, what if some of the bus passengers need to buy a new car on the road?
For some reason, when we build a capital transport hub, we always get a shopping center.
Recently, the situation reached its logical conclusion, when it was decided to give part of the parking lot for the market.
Now, on the third floor of the Planernaya transport hub, among the parking spaces marked on the floor, there is a brisk trade.
Vegetables, spices, Chinese jeans, non-Russian speech and security guards glaring at our photographer.
The interchange hub has finally turned into a bazaar.
The fact is that earlier there was a market near the Planernaya metro station, but it was demolished.
And in the prefecture, they took pity on the merchants and let them into the intercepting parking lot of the transfer hub.
Anyway, because of the high prices there is always empty.
The funny thing is that the market was demolished in order to build in its place ... a new planar TPU.
Such is the castling.
At the Kaluzhskaya metro station, the approach distance from the metro lobby to the bus was 50 meters, - says Alexander Morozov.
After the construction of a shopping center, allegedly a transport hub, the distance increased to 170 meters.
To get on the bus, you need to go through the entire shopping center.
After 22 hours, when it is closed, you have to go around it in the open.
However, the structures at Planernaya and Kaluzhskaya will soon look like flowers.
In mid-September, the Town Planning and Land Commission of the Mayor&#39;s Office approved planning decisions for the first eight capital transfer hubs.
Four of them will be 25-storey, not counting two or three underground tiers.
The main monster will grow near the Tushino metro station, it will have 418.7 thousand square meters. meters of area.
Representatives of the directorate of railway stations of the Russian Railways, who are responsible for the construction of the transfer hub near the metro, have already told reporters that the future high-rise buildings will house shops, hotels and apartments.
At the same time, officials assure that multi-storey parking lots will occupy from a third to a half of the area.
Let&#39;s take &quot;people&#39;s&quot; garages as an example.
Let&#39;s say a garage for 258 cars, which was recently built on International Street, has an area of 8015 square meters. meters.
This means that for parking for 2,600 cars, Petrovsko-Razumovskaya will need about 80,000 square meters.
This is less than a third of the colossus that they are going to build there.
Let one or two floors go to all sorts of platforms for buses.
Remains at least 150 thousand square meters. meters of commercial real estate.
And this, for a moment, is almost two GUM.
If capital transfer hubs near stations and railway stations are being built by railway workers, then the rest of the sites will be developed by metro workers.
They also promised that there would be many &quot;functional facilities&quot;, including hotels, offices and even gyms.
By the way, the Moscow City Property Department recently told reporters that they are developing a draft resolution, according to which investors will be able to apply directly to officials for obtaining a site for TPU.
Without any competition.
Because, they say, transport issues for the city are a priority.
An ideal transport hub is, for example, the Harvard station in Boston or the Spadine station in Toronto, Alexander Morozov is sure.
There, trolleybuses and trams go underground to the level of the metro and the approach distance from the metro car to the tram is only 50 meters without access to the street.
There is no extra trade around.
But Moscow officials are thrown into extremes.
Either we will not build anything, or we will build 25 floors with offices and apartments.
