Bombardier&#39;s profit falls as deliveries and aircraft orders fall
Bombardier Corp., a Canadian aircraft and train maker, reported a 15 percent drop in net profit Thursday, driven by lower third-quarter aircraft orders and deliveries and contract problems in its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier also did not release any flight test data for its latest CSeries aircraft or provide new information on whether the aircraft&#39;s ambitious plans to enter commercial service by next September will be met.
The prototype aircraft has only flown three more times since its first flight about a month and a half ago, raising questions about whether the test phase is on schedule.
The results fell short of forecasts and sent stocks down more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, cut his estimate Thursday from &quot;above market&quot; to &quot;mid market&quot; on the belief that stock gains are limited for the next quarter or two.
“While the decline in aircraft deliveries was broadly predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the transportation department&#39;s earnings performance,” Doerksen said in a stock market review.
We believe that Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we assume the market will become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to carve out a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is currently dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype aircraft was unveiled in March and flew for the first time in September after several months of delay.
However, firm orders for the CSeries are still low at 177 as potential buyers wait for flight test results to test the company&#39;s claims about the new jet&#39;s fuel efficiency and potential economy.
In total, there are now 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Pierre Beaudoin was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft entered commercial service.
On Thursday, executives also assured analysts and the media that the program was moving forward as planned.
&quot;The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected,&quot; Beaudoin said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were scheduled during the aircraft&#39;s downtime.
All manufacturers plan testing differently.
We decided to make the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will continue throughout the flight test program.
The second of five test units is due to fly in the coming weeks and the rest will soon follow, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical about the claim that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is evaluating the commissioning timeline and will provide new information in the next few months.
&quot;This slow pace of flight testing - while apparently in line with Bombardier&#39;s internal schedule - reinforces our view that commissioning will be pushed back to the first quarter of 2015,&quot; Doerksen said.
In the third quarter ended Sept. 30, Bombardier&#39;s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents a share, from $172 million, or 9 cents a share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same at 9 cents.
Gross revenue declined slightly, from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts were expecting earnings of 10 cents per share and gross income of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world&#39;s fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer said it delivered 45 aircraft in the quarter, down from 57 the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The aerospace division&#39;s order book was $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
“In aerospace, the results were in line with our goals, but the low number of incoming orders and general market conditions were a nuisance,” Beaudoin said.
Gross aerospace revenue fell 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world&#39;s largest train maker, said gross revenue in the sector rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The order book in the transportation division was $32.6 billion as of September 30, up slightly from December 31.
The revenues of the transportation division were negatively affected by problems with the execution of several large contracts.
The management said that a new development plan will be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google&#39;s chief financial officer Patrick Pichette will join the board of directors, fell 8.5 percent to C$4.83 in mid-Thursday trading.
Brazil&#39;s Embraer SA, the world&#39;s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier&#39;s closest competitor, reported a 10 percent drop in quarterly revenue on Thursday.
