Two YMCA employees indicted for sex crimes before Jonathan Lord charges, Royal Commission has learned
Two YMCA NSW employees were charged with child sex crimes before charges were filed in 2011 against Karingbach childcare worker Jonathan Lord, the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse told the Royal Commission.
But the commission&#39;s opening statement said it &quot;has never dealt with cases of child sexual abuse within its organization.&quot;
CEO Philip Hare was asked about one case where a YMCA worker was charged with child pornography offenses and another when a gym instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sex crimes against children under his care in 1991 year.
Mr Hare told Gail Furness, the lawyer assisting the commission, that he knew about the first case but did not know about the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA also made an inaccuracy in its opening speech to the commission, stating that &quot;there were external reviews of the YMCA that recognized that the YMCA is at the forefront of child safety.&quot;
The evidence presented to the commission indicates that the YMCA was notified that it received the second lowest of four possible ratings in a quality audit conducted by the Department of Education and Communities in August of this year.
Mr. Hare, who joined the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that he and lower management made a mistake in hiring Lord and also failed to ensure staff clearly understood their obligation to report child safety violations.
Earlier this year Lord was convicted of sex crimes against 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was imprisoned for at least six years.
But Mr. Hare dismissed the suggestion that the YMCA&#39;s corporate ethics prevented employees from reporting Lord&#39;s child safety violations.
Employees testified that they observed violations, including that Lord was alone with the children, personally looked after them, sat them on his lap, said that he loved one of them and allowed them to play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Oakwell, who was under Lord&#39;s care and asked to be trained in child protection because she was concerned about his behavior, testified that she found Jackie Barnat, child care manager for the Karingbach YMCA who was Lord&#39;s supervisor, &quot;very intimidating and often inaccessible.&quot;
The chief executive said that he did not accept employees&#39; explanations that they were embarrassed to report the situation to their superiors.
Rather, he said, their friendship with the Lord took them away from the need to report him.
Mr Hare said he presented to the New South Wales YMCA board his view that the lesson for the organization from the &quot;Jonathan Lord incident&quot; was not &quot;about providing information&quot; by employees, and the board agreed.
Mr Hare said the decision to force employees to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations surfaced was taken by YMCA Child Custody CEO Liam Wheatley.
He said it was intended to prevent corruption of evidence, but was &quot;overdone&quot; and poorly implemented.
YMCA NSW was not a child-safe organization during Jonathan Lord&#39;s tenure from 2009-2011, child molestation expert Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University told the commission.
He said there were &quot;serious problems&quot; in recruiting, selecting, instructing, training and supervising staff.
The hearing has been adjourned until December 20.
