We can safely say that New York is the birthplace of stand-up comedy in America: almost a century ago, entertainer Frank Fay, who worked as an entertainer at the Palace Theater on Broadway, began telling jokes directly to the public in a colloquial manner.
Fei&#39;s innovation has been picked up over time by others, most recently by the New York Comedy Festival.
Created and curated by Caroline Hirsch, founder of the Carolines stand-up club, the festival celebrates its tenth anniversary this year with over sixty shows in small clubs and big theaters.
&quot;Most of these headliners started out at the Carolines and then went on to become more successful, to the point where they&#39;re too famous to play at the club,&quot; Hirsch said.
We created this festival as a way to continue working with them.
